The start symbol expands as

S → NT91 NT22

NT91 can only generate the single terminal t8, so the very first symbol of any sentence in the language is t8 – which matches the first token of the string.

NT22 has two possibilities:

1. NT22 → 't8'             (gives just one more terminal, t8)
2. NT22 → NT87 NT98     (gives two sub-blocks in sequence)

Because the second token of the string is t7 (not t8), NT22 must take the second alternative:

NT22 → NT87 NT98.

NT87 itself is completely fixed:

NT87 → NT95 NT53
NT95 → 't7'
NT53 → 't6'

Hence NT87 produces exactly the two-symbol block t7 t6.  Consequently the second and third tokens of any string generated by the grammar must be

… t7 t6 …

– which fits our string (tokens 2 and 3).

Now the remainder of the string (tokens 4 … end) has to be generated by NT98.  
NT98 has only two forms:

a) NT98 → 't5'          (one terminal)
b) NT98 → NT90 NT87    (two blocks, the second of which is again t7 t6)

The rest of the given string is 38 tokens long, so we must choose option (b).  
That means the very last two tokens of the entire sentence must be the fixed pair t7 t6 produced by the final NT87.

But the last two tokens of the string provided are t2 t6, not t7 t6.

Therefore no derivation from the grammar can yield the given string.

Answer: No
